lly do that, but it feels unrelated although it aligns with the rules. However, it acts as a placeholder, so deleting it might not be wise. If there's no dynamic coverage, it shouldn't be an issue. Still, making it public could be harmless, and I need to check JUnit/Jupiter/AssertJ styles for our writes.\\\"}]}\"}, {\"type\": \"toolCall\", \"id\": \"call_RySqVYRbvt0dMdwoD6lhEfB7|fc_05de0b0dbd8df16a0169f28abbb63c8191ade895e99bca77ec\", \"name\": \"write\", \"arguments\": {\"path\": \"tests/src/org.apache.commons/commons-crypto/1.1.0/src/test/java/org_apache_commons/commons_crypto/ReflectionUtilsTest.java\", \"content\": \"/*\\n * Copyright and related rights waived via CC0\\n *\\n * You should have received a copy of the CC0 legalcode along with this\\n * work. If not, see <http://creativecommons.org/publicdomain/zero/1.0/>.\\n */\\npackage org_apache_commons.commons_crypto;\\n\\nimport static org.assertj.core.api.Assertions.assertThat;\\n\\nimport java.util.Properties;\\n\\nimport org.apache.commons.crypto.random.CryptoRandom;\\nimport org.apache.commons.crypto.random.CryptoRandomFactory;\\nimport org.apache.commons.crypto.utils.ReflectionUtils;\\nimport org.junit.jupiter.api.Test;\\n\\npublic class ReflectionUtilsTest {\\n    @Test\\n    void getClassByNameLoadsRequestedCommonsCryptoClass() throws Exception {\\n        final Class<?> randomClass = ReflectionUtils.getClassByName(\\n                CryptoRandomFactory.RandomProvider.JAVA.getClassName());\\n\\n        assertThat(randomClass).isSameAs(CryptoRandomFactory.RandomProvider.JAVA.getImplClass());\\n    }\\n\\n    @Test\\n    void newInstanceCreatesObjectWithNoArgumentConstructor() {\\n        final ReflectionUtils reflectionUtils = ReflectionUtils.newInstance(ReflectionUtils.class);\\n\\n        assertThat(reflectionUtils).isInstanceOf(ReflectionUtils.class);\\n    }\\n\\n    @Test\\n    void cryptoRandomFactoryCreatesJavaProviderThroughReflectionUtils() throws Exception {\\n        final Properties properties = new Properties();\\n        properties.setProperty(CryptoRandomFactory.CLASSES_KEY, CryptoRandomFactory.RandomProvider.JAVA.getClassName());\\n        final byte[] randomBytes = new byte[16];\\n\\n        try (CryptoRandom random = CryptoRandomFactory.getCryptoRandom(properties)) {\\n            random.nextBytes(randomBytes);\\n        }\\n\\n        assertThat(randomBytes).containsAnyOf(nonZeroByteValues());\\n    }\\n\\n    private static Byte[] nonZeroByteValues() {\\n        final Byte[] values = new Byte[255];\\n        for (int value = 1; value <= 255; value++) {\\n            values[value - 1] = (byte) value;\\n        }\\n        return values;\\n    }\\n}\\n\"}}], \"api\": \"openai-responses\", \"provider\": \"OCA\", \"model\": \"gpt-5.5\", \"usage\": {\"input\": 2372, \"output\": 1028, \"cacheRead\": 23040, \"cacheWrite\": 0, \"totalTokens\": 26440, \"cost\": {\"input\": 0, \"output\": 0, \"cacheRead\": 0, \"cacheWrite\": 0, \"total\": 0}}, \"stopReason\": \"toolUse\", \"timestamp\": 1777502896668, \"responseId\": \"resp_05de0b0dbd8df16a0169f28ab1216081918eed9d52b7fb45ef\"}}\n../3024-4cce8920/human-intervention-logs/org.apache.commons:commons-crypto:1.1.0/add-new-library-support/pi-generation-2026-04-29T22-49-42-730363Z.log:2170:[recv] {\"type\": \"turn_end\", \"message\": {\"role\": \"assistant\", \"content\": [{\"type\": \"thinking\", \"thinking\": \"**Considering test visibility**\\n\\nI’m thinking about whether to make Commons_cryptoTest public since the existing non-public tests will remain intact. Maybe I should actually do that, but it feels unrelated although it aligns with the rules. However, it acts as a placeholder, so deleting it might not be wise. If there's no dynamic coverage, it shouldn't be an issue. Still, making it public could be harmless, and I need to check JUnit/Jupiter/AssertJ styles for our writes.\", \"thinkingSignature\": \"{\\\"id\\\":\\\"rs_05de0b0dbd8df16a0169f28ab1bfa881918974039d1a085d96\\\",\\\"type\\\":\\\"reasoning\\